There are type errors in our modified files. Let me focus on the relevant one:

```
src/routes/(protected)/(app)/clients/index.tsx(71,9): error TS2322: Type '{ input: { archived: boolean | undefined; assigneeId: string[] | undefined; cursor: string | undefined; limit: number; search: string | undefined; }; } & Omit<QueryOptionsBase<{ items: { archived: boolean; ... 10 more ...; assignee: { ...; }; }[]; nextCursor: string | null; }, Error>, "input">' is not assignable to type 'UseQueryOptions<ListQueryResult<{ archived: boolean; assigneeId: string; ... }>>'.
```

The issue is that the oRPC procedure returns `nextCursor: string | null` but `ListQueryResult<TItem>` has `nextCursor?: string` (which is `string | undefined`). `null` is not assignable to `undefined`.

I have two options:
1. Change `ListQueryResult` to have `nextCursor: string | null` instead of `nextCursor?: string`
2. Make `buildQueryOptions` return a looser type

Option 1 is better because it matches the actual oRPC return type. Let me fix it.

Actually, looking more carefully, `nextCursor?: string` means the property can be `undefined` or missing, while `nextCursor: string | null` means the property is always present but can be `null`. These are different types. The oRPC return type has `nextCursor: string | null`, which is more specific.

Let me change `ListQueryResult` to match the actual oRPC return shape:
```ts
type ListQueryResult<TItem> = {
  items: TItem[];
  nextCursor: string | null;
};
```

And then in the component, I'll treat `null` as "no more pages" instead of `undefined`:

```ts
const nextCursor = queryResult.data?.nextCursor;
// ...
{nextCursor && ( ... )}
```

`nextCursor` will be `string | null | undefined`. When it's a non-empty string, we show "Load more". `null` or `undefined` means no more pages. The `nextCursor && ...` check handles both correctly.

Wait, but there might be other procedures that return `nextCursor?: string` (optional/undefined) instead of `nextCursor: string | null`. Let me make the type accommodate both:

```ts
type ListQueryResult<TItem> = {
  items: TItem[];
  nextCursor?: string | null;
};
